# React Development - Cursor Rules

## Core Principles

### Effects are an Escape Hatch
- Effects let you synchronize components with external systems (network, browser APIs, third-party libraries)
- If there's no external system involved, you probably don't need an Effect
- Most logic should be in event handlers or calculated during rendering

### Rendering Must Be Pure
- Don't perform side effects during rendering
- Side effects belong in event handlers or Effects
- Rendering should only calculate JSX output

---

## When You DON'T Need Effects

### ❌ Avoid: Transforming Data for Rendering
```javascript
// 🔴 BAD - unnecessary Effect and state
function Form() {
  const [firstName, setFirstName] = useState('');
  const [lastName, setLastName] = useState('');
  const [fullName, setFullName] = useState('');
  
  useEffect(() => {
    setFullName(firstName + ' ' + lastName);
  }, [firstName, lastName]);
}

// ✅ GOOD - calculate during rendering
function Form() {
  const [firstName, setFirstName] = useState('');
  const [lastName, setLastName] = useState('');
  const fullName = firstName + ' ' + lastName;
}
```

**Rule**: If something can be calculated from existing props/state, calculate it during rendering. Don't store it in state.

### ❌ Avoid: Effects for Event-Specific Logic
```javascript
// 🔴 BAD - event logic in Effect
function ProductPage({ product }) {
  useEffect(() => {
    if (product.isInCart) {
      showNotification(`Added ${product.name}`);
    }
  }, [product]);
}

// ✅ GOOD - event logic in event handler
function ProductPage({ product, addToCart }) {
  function handleBuyClick() {
    addToCart(product);
    showNotification(`Added ${product.name}`);
  }
}
```

**Rule**: If logic should run because the user did something specific (clicked, typed, etc.), put it in an event handler, not an Effect.

### ❌ Avoid: Chains of Effects
```javascript
// 🔴 BAD - chain of Effects updating each other
useEffect(() => {
  if (card !== null && card.gold) {
    setGoldCardCount(c => c + 1);
  }
}, [card]);

useEffect(() => {
  if (goldCardCount > 3) {
    setRound(r => r + 1);
    setGoldCardCount(0);
  }
}, [goldCardCount]);

// ✅ GOOD - calculate and update in event handler
function handlePlaceCard(nextCard) {
  setCard(nextCard);
  if (nextCard.gold) {
    if (goldCardCount < 3) {
      setGoldCardCount(goldCardCount + 1);
    } else {
      setGoldCardCount(0);
      setRound(round + 1);
    }
  }
}
```

**Rule**: Calculate what you can during rendering, update state in event handlers. Avoid Effect chains.

