## Refs Usage

### When to Use Refs
Use refs for values that don't affect rendering:
- Timeout/interval IDs
- DOM elements
- External library instances
- Any value that doesn't need to trigger re-renders

```javascript
// ✅ GOOD - ref for non-rendering value
function Stopwatch() {
  const intervalRef = useRef(null);
  
  function handleStart() {
    intervalRef.current = setInterval(() => {
      setNow(Date.now());
    }, 10);
  }
  
  function handleStop() {
    clearInterval(intervalRef.current);
  }
}
```

### Refs vs State

| Use Refs When: | Use State When: |
|----------------|-----------------|
| Value doesn't affect render output | Value affects what's displayed |
| Updating doesn't need re-render | Updating should re-render |
| Storing timeout IDs, DOM nodes | Storing form inputs, toggles, lists |
| Reading in event handlers only | Reading during render |

### Ref Best Practices

1. **Don't read/write `ref.current` during rendering**
```javascript
// 🔴 BAD - reading ref during render
function Component() {
  const ref = useRef(0);
  const value = ref.current; // Unpredictable!
  return <div>{value}</div>;
}

// ✅ GOOD - reading ref in event handler
function Component() {
  const ref = useRef(0);
  function handleClick() {
    console.log(ref.current); // Safe!
  }
}
```

2. **Exception: Lazy initialization**
```javascript
// ✅ OK - one-time initialization during first render
function Component() {
  const ref = useRef(null);
  if (ref.current === null) {
    ref.current = new ExpensiveThing();
  }
}
```

